WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:11.280
Hello all, we're going to be talking about how to create reproducible reports with R.

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:14.040
My name is Braulio Cuandon, this is my partner Ana Santos.

00:00:14.040 --> 00:00:19.879
I'll be going over the scenario, the regulations, the restrictions, and the goals we faced in

00:00:19.879 --> 00:00:20.879
this project.

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:24.879
Ana will be going over the project, the program itself, and the program features.

00:00:24.879 --> 00:00:32.200
Just a little background, we work for BWI, and last year, around January, July, we were

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:37.439
tasked with creating an R program that can write engineering reports for engineers.

00:00:37.439 --> 00:00:44.360
A bit more background, so BWI, Biosense Webster, is a leader in the science of diagnosing and

00:00:44.360 --> 00:00:48.200
treating heart rhythm disorders, specifically AFib.

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:53.599
AFib can lead to strokes, heart failures, and blood clots.

00:00:53.599 --> 00:00:59.119
And since we develop a product that comes in contact with the heart itself, we are

00:00:59.119 --> 00:01:05.000
heavily regulated by the FDA in the documentation section, specifically our reports.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:11.879
We have strict guidelines to how our reports are composed and presented to the FDA.

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:17.000
BWI itself generates about over 1,000 reports a year.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.160
Each report takes about four work days, so that's a total of 30 quick hours.

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:26.440
So just doing quick math, 1,000 reports, 32 hours, let's say engineer one makes about

00:01:26.440 --> 00:01:27.440
$25 an hour.

00:01:27.440 --> 00:01:30.599
It's a lot of money and time wasted.

00:01:30.599 --> 00:01:34.160
So we wanted to eliminate all that.

00:01:34.160 --> 00:01:40.400
However, due to how strict our procedures are, their methods are, we have very strict

00:01:40.400 --> 00:01:47.800
regulations when it comes to writing the report itself, so strict that even minor errors or

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:52.760
deviations from our templates often result in rejections.

00:01:52.760 --> 00:01:58.360
This is actually an example of a report we generated with our program.

00:01:58.360 --> 00:02:02.400
As you can see, it looks just like a regular Word document, which is great because that's

00:02:02.400 --> 00:02:04.199
what we were aiming for.

00:02:04.199 --> 00:02:09.039
We wanted to pass through our documentation system without any kickback, and we could

00:02:09.039 --> 00:02:15.279
not do that with HTML or PDF, so we had to rely heavily on the Word format.

00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:20.520
We did manage to get about two reports into our documentation system without the approvers

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:25.679
themselves noticing that this was our generated program.

00:02:25.679 --> 00:02:27.600
We do have certain regulations we had to follow.

00:02:27.600 --> 00:02:32.360
For example, all our reports are required to have a cover page, and in that cover page

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:38.039
we are required to have a title, the location of the document, the author's name, and the

00:02:38.039 --> 00:02:39.639
date it was generated.

00:02:39.639 --> 00:02:46.759
In our headers, we are required to have our logo, the test study, the title, the number,

00:02:46.759 --> 00:02:49.360
the revisions, and the pagination.

00:02:49.360 --> 00:02:56.240
All this is really hard to do with Word, and we had very, very many setbacks with this.

00:02:56.240 --> 00:02:59.720
Moving towards the body, we do have regulations on our headers.

00:02:59.720 --> 00:03:06.119
They must be numbered in sequential order, and certain sections must contain specific

00:03:06.119 --> 00:03:07.440
content.

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:10.960
We also had regulations with our table.

00:03:10.960 --> 00:03:16.440
All the headers should be highlighted in gray so the reviewer could see the difference between

00:03:16.440 --> 00:03:19.679
headers and actual data.

00:03:19.679 --> 00:03:22.399
We also had regulations that came to our stat methods.

00:03:22.399 --> 00:03:29.320
This example of a process capability, whenever we do histograms or process capability studies,

00:03:29.320 --> 00:03:32.520
we are required to show the CPK.

00:03:32.520 --> 00:03:39.119
Anything below 1.3 will generate a rationale on why it's allowed.

00:03:39.119 --> 00:03:42.759
Just a quick walkthrough for our lifecycle of a report.

00:03:42.759 --> 00:03:48.160
Like I said before, it takes about four days to generate a report.

00:03:48.160 --> 00:03:50.880
After we generate a report, we send it out for approvals.

00:03:50.880 --> 00:03:55.399
From then, it takes about two weeks to hear back from our approvers.

00:03:55.399 --> 00:03:56.600
Our approvers are really busy.

00:03:56.600 --> 00:04:00.160
They're usually higher level engineers.

00:04:00.160 --> 00:04:05.440
Taking about three hours of the time to review our report is another money pit.

00:04:05.440 --> 00:04:09.119
If they find anything, they're going to reject it, kick it back, and we have to redo the

00:04:09.119 --> 00:04:10.119
process.

00:04:10.119 --> 00:04:14.399
We have to spend about another two hours of their own time and our time to fix any issues,

00:04:14.399 --> 00:04:15.919
and then the cycle begins again.

00:04:15.919 --> 00:04:20.559
You can see after constant rejections how many hours of the day and how much time we

00:04:20.559 --> 00:04:25.959
waste with just writing a simple report.

00:04:25.959 --> 00:04:29.119
These are some kind of errors we usually find.

00:04:29.119 --> 00:04:30.799
We'll be using the wrong kind of template.

00:04:30.799 --> 00:04:35.359
For example, someone used a Rev G version of the template instead of the newest Rev

00:04:35.359 --> 00:04:42.519
H. This is very common since our engineers like to get previous approved reports and

00:04:42.519 --> 00:04:45.000
modify them for their studies.

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:47.200
This is another example.

00:04:47.200 --> 00:04:54.079
When they revise previous reports, they don't verify if they changed all the product names

00:04:54.079 --> 00:04:56.320
or if there's any contradicting statements.

00:04:56.320 --> 00:05:00.920
For example, we're talking about catheter body in the purpose, but in scope we're talking

00:05:00.920 --> 00:05:02.640
about catheter tip.

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:06.119
That's a contradiction that will get us in trouble with the FDA.

00:05:06.119 --> 00:05:10.799
We're also talking about 32 samples, but in the acceptance criteria we only have about

00:05:10.799 --> 00:05:12.079
30.

00:05:12.079 --> 00:05:17.519
There's also inconsistency with our lot numbers and our units.

00:05:17.519 --> 00:05:20.359
Some restrictions we faced is our rigid system.

00:05:20.359 --> 00:05:26.119
We had to follow our template to the T or else it would get rejected and we have to

00:05:26.119 --> 00:05:28.880
lose more time making a report.

00:05:28.880 --> 00:05:33.399
The second one is we have to submit it in a Word document.

00:05:33.399 --> 00:05:39.040
Using our markdown with Word was one of the biggest hurdles for us.

00:05:39.040 --> 00:05:44.399
A lot of the packages do not work with Word output, so we had to figure out little tricky

00:05:44.399 --> 00:05:47.600
ways to get around it.

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:51.920
Our overall goal for the project was, one, limit it as much time as possible it takes

00:05:52.119 --> 00:05:59.160
to generate a report, two, make it super simple that it could be done in one click, three,

00:05:59.160 --> 00:06:06.160
review the user's input to make sure there's no mathematical errors, no grammatical errors,

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:08.679
or any stat errors.

00:06:08.679 --> 00:06:14.440
Then finally, our last goal was we wanted to make this program flexible as possible

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:16.279
to be used for a variety of tests.

00:06:16.279 --> 00:06:20.320
We did not want a one-trick pony report.

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:24.799
I'm going to hand the mic over to my partner, Anna Santos, who will be reviewing the program

00:06:24.799 --> 00:06:26.559
and the program features.

00:06:26.559 --> 00:06:31.399
Anna Santos Thank you.

00:06:31.399 --> 00:06:37.079
As you can see, you have found how cumbersome it could be to make the reports.

00:06:37.079 --> 00:06:44.320
What approach did we do to actually improve this process?

00:06:44.320 --> 00:06:48.959
First we specified the reference document within our YAML header.

00:06:48.959 --> 00:06:54.880
The reference document would serve as the backbone of the rest of the documents that

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:56.839
we are going to generate.

00:06:56.839 --> 00:07:03.200
Within the styles of the headings and the Word document, what we did was to edit the

00:07:03.200 --> 00:07:04.200
headings.

00:07:04.200 --> 00:07:09.760
For example, we wanted to edit the font, the color, the size, and the indention.

00:07:09.760 --> 00:07:17.320
That way we could mimic how the text are supposed to be shown within the specified procedures

00:07:17.320 --> 00:07:19.359
within our document system.

00:07:19.359 --> 00:07:24.040
We also specified that Word document, of course, is what we wanted as an output because this

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:31.000
is the only type of document that is allowed within our document management system.

00:07:31.000 --> 00:07:36.679
As much as we wanted to standardize the report generation procedure, we also wanted to give

00:07:36.679 --> 00:07:43.640
our users the flexibility to actually be able to customize their reports in their own ways

00:07:43.640 --> 00:07:48.720
because each engineer does different types of testings, and this would require different

00:07:48.720 --> 00:07:49.720
types of analysis.

00:07:49.720 --> 00:07:57.079
For this one, we required them to input a raw data spreadsheet, which includes the specifications

00:07:57.079 --> 00:07:59.399
of the testing that they have performed.

00:07:59.399 --> 00:08:05.040
We also have text input sections where we could capture the details of the title of

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:09.600
the testing that was performed and who is the author of the report.

00:08:09.600 --> 00:08:15.480
Also to give them a flexibility when it comes to analyzing, we let them choose from a pool

00:08:15.480 --> 00:08:20.880
of options of what types of plots they are able to show.

00:08:20.880 --> 00:08:26.959
And with that, I mentioned earlier that users are required to input a raw data spreadsheet.

00:08:26.959 --> 00:08:32.000
Now you're going to ask what are the typical things that are within the raw data spreadsheet.

00:08:32.239 --> 00:08:40.359
So this is an example of a toned down raw data spreadsheet, and within here, the specifications

00:08:40.359 --> 00:08:45.200
of the testing is shown, such as the title of the testing that was performed, what are

00:08:45.200 --> 00:08:51.440
the steps that has been done in order to follow the procedure of the testing, and in here

00:08:51.440 --> 00:08:56.400
we could see the values that were gathered within the testing that has been performed,

00:08:56.400 --> 00:09:02.440
and also the bounds on which or wherein the measured data should fall into.

00:09:02.440 --> 00:09:08.359
And within this raw data input, what we do is check the data for any types of inconsistencies.

00:09:08.359 --> 00:09:12.159
Let's say there's inconsistencies within dates.

00:09:12.159 --> 00:09:14.159
We are trying to catch that early on.

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:18.280
That way it doesn't get escalated into a higher level problem.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:24.919
We also look into the errors within grammar and spelling, and also we look for drastic

00:09:24.919 --> 00:09:30.000
outliers because we wanted this to be a potential problem in the future if it's just a little

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:32.640
typographical error.

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:37.960
And also, you know, sometimes our engineers are rushing their reports, furiously typing,

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:42.119
and sometimes accidentally they hit the caps lock on, and we don't want it to be shown

00:09:42.119 --> 00:09:46.799
in their report because what we wanted to show is something in title case as shown in

00:09:46.799 --> 00:09:48.960
the photo below.

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:51.280
So stringer is really helpful to do that.

00:09:51.280 --> 00:09:56.159
The function string to upper and string to title helps us to be able to control this

00:09:56.159 --> 00:09:59.400
user inputs.

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:07.000
Now the report generation procedures using R and having it in a reproducible manner was

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:08.280
never easy.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:12.640
There's a lot of things that are hurdles along the way.

00:10:12.640 --> 00:10:17.799
So the first one is that the Word document headers were a little bit difficult to edit,

00:10:17.799 --> 00:10:23.559
especially if you wanted the text to appear dynamically as the users input them.

00:10:23.559 --> 00:10:31.159
And there's also hurdles within actually outputting the tables that are following the specific

00:10:31.159 --> 00:10:34.799
procedures that was outlined within our documents.

00:10:34.799 --> 00:10:41.239
And also having users with different backgrounds, different locations, be able to access this

00:10:41.239 --> 00:10:44.440
change within the process of generating the reports.

00:10:44.440 --> 00:10:49.640
And also, lastly, for users to further be able to customize the reports that they're

00:10:49.640 --> 00:10:51.640
trying to make.

00:10:51.640 --> 00:10:57.599
So how did we edit the Word document headers based off the users inputs?

00:10:57.599 --> 00:11:02.400
So what we did is we have a reference document wherein we have keywords.

00:11:02.400 --> 00:11:05.599
As you can see, the second photo has quadruple X.

00:11:05.599 --> 00:11:09.440
So we wanted to edit the quadruple X with the user input.

00:11:09.440 --> 00:11:16.479
So packages officer is really helpful for this, specifically the headers replace all

00:11:16.479 --> 00:11:17.840
text function.

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:20.520
What it does is it looks for the keyword.

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:26.400
And this keyword is replaced by the input, which, for example, is chapter tip diameter.

00:11:26.400 --> 00:11:32.039
And then with this, this print function will save this in a specific path.

00:11:32.039 --> 00:11:37.000
And this will be the reference document that will be specified in the YAML header.

00:11:37.000 --> 00:11:43.919
That way, going forward, all the documents that will be printed by the user will be as

00:11:43.919 --> 00:11:51.840
such, because we wanted these tiles and revision levels to appear in the actual output.

00:11:51.840 --> 00:11:58.960
So now, as specified earlier, there's specific formatting that has to be followed when it

00:11:58.960 --> 00:12:01.919
comes to the tables that we're trying to generate.

00:12:01.919 --> 00:12:08.159
And officer and flex table was really useful for such, because we were able to make beautiful

00:12:08.159 --> 00:12:11.840
tables and actually output it in Word.

00:12:11.840 --> 00:12:17.359
And Pandoc is definitely essential for having this done, because it gives us a success to

00:12:17.359 --> 00:12:20.000
be able to output it in Word.

00:12:20.000 --> 00:12:25.559
And another feature that we like the most with officer and flex table is the style function,

00:12:25.559 --> 00:12:28.340
wherein we could add a conditional statement.

00:12:28.340 --> 00:12:33.859
So within the conditional statement, what we do is the measure data, which in this case

00:12:33.859 --> 00:12:35.859
is tip diameter.

00:12:35.859 --> 00:12:42.700
We'll look if it is below the lower specification limit or above the upper specification limit.

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:48.099
And if it does, then we wanted to highlight it, because this is probably a potential type

00:12:48.099 --> 00:12:50.700
of concern that we wanted to address early on.

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:56.859
So what we do is we change the text of the color in red and also italicize the text.

00:12:56.859 --> 00:13:01.179
That way, it catches the user's attention.

00:13:01.179 --> 00:13:07.619
And then going forward, we wanted people within the company with different backgrounds, different

00:13:07.619 --> 00:13:13.260
skill sets, and different locations to be able to access this type of methodology.

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:18.820
So with that, we decided to leverage the Johnson & Johnson Shiny server.

00:13:18.820 --> 00:13:25.979
And within that, we deployed a Shiny app that has this, our markdown, wrapped.

00:13:25.979 --> 00:13:31.419
And with this, it allowed for users to access it within a web link, put their inputs.

00:13:31.419 --> 00:13:37.539
And once they hit generate report, they could automatically have the report properly formatted

00:13:37.539 --> 00:13:40.059
within their downloads folder.

00:13:40.059 --> 00:13:46.739
Also, we were able to add more features for further customizations of the plots that the

00:13:46.739 --> 00:13:49.500
users want to actually generate.

00:13:49.500 --> 00:13:55.659
So for example, here, if the user uploads the raw data spreadsheet, the column headers

00:13:55.659 --> 00:13:58.580
within the raw data spreadsheet is red.

00:13:58.580 --> 00:14:05.340
And once this is red, the dropdown menus for the scatterplot x-axis and scatterplot y-axis

00:14:05.340 --> 00:14:08.500
is automatically updated with the column headers.

00:14:08.500 --> 00:14:09.820
Why do we want this?

00:14:09.820 --> 00:14:14.179
It's because the raw data spreadsheet column headers could be edited by the users, and

00:14:14.179 --> 00:14:20.940
we want them to be comfortable as possible and easy for them to be able to generate these plots.

00:14:20.940 --> 00:14:26.140
This is an example of a plot that was generated by the user.

00:14:26.140 --> 00:14:33.020
Now we showed you little snippets of how the report looks like by going over a few of our

00:14:33.020 --> 00:14:34.020
methodology.

00:14:34.020 --> 00:14:38.299
Now, what's a nice thing on the cake, we want to show you an example output.

00:14:38.299 --> 00:14:44.260
Keep in mind that these are not actual data, and it's only used for demonstration purposes

00:14:44.260 --> 00:14:45.979
only.

00:14:45.979 --> 00:14:50.340
So that is the title page with the title and the author name.

00:14:50.340 --> 00:14:55.299
We have the sections with the subsequent parts of the sections properly indented.

00:14:55.299 --> 00:14:57.179
We have tables.

00:14:57.179 --> 00:14:59.140
We have the table for equipment.

00:14:59.140 --> 00:15:01.979
We have procedures that are shown sequentially.

00:15:01.979 --> 00:15:06.820
We have the failure highlighted in red within the raw data table.

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:10.619
Then we have more observations, as you can see.

00:15:10.619 --> 00:15:14.619
And then further down the document, we have scatterplots.

00:15:14.619 --> 00:15:20.219
We have boxplots with the failure highlighted in red, as shown as the outlier.

00:15:21.099 --> 00:15:23.099
We have normality plots.

00:15:23.099 --> 00:15:29.059
We have capability histograms, and the table below that shows capability measurements that

00:15:29.059 --> 00:15:30.059
were also calculated.

00:15:30.059 --> 00:15:36.099
And also below, we could see, for example, the recommendation, and this is a subsequent

00:15:36.099 --> 00:15:39.739
paragraph that is in the introduction of the section.

00:15:39.739 --> 00:15:41.340
It's properly indented.

00:15:41.340 --> 00:15:44.179
And then the actual recommendation is further indented.

00:15:44.179 --> 00:15:50.179
So these are the little things that we made sure is also captured.

00:15:50.179 --> 00:15:54.619
Now, what do we want you to take away from this presentation?

00:15:54.619 --> 00:15:59.419
You may think that the methodology shown might not be as complex.

00:15:59.419 --> 00:16:04.940
But the key idea here that we learned along the way is we wanted to challenge all of you.

00:16:04.940 --> 00:16:10.380
We wanted to challenge each one of you as you go back home through your individual organizations.

00:16:10.380 --> 00:16:18.380
We want you to promote the idea of reproducible data analysis with your individual organizations.

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:23.260
Because along the way, we've seen how it is important within a company.

00:16:23.260 --> 00:16:27.940
We wanted you to be able to eliminate documentation errors.

00:16:27.940 --> 00:16:35.580
And once you do that, you could actually be able to focus on higher-level issues.

00:16:35.580 --> 00:16:40.219
Also, this is just one application of reproducible data analysis.

00:16:40.219 --> 00:16:46.539
And we know that on your different job functions, you could also implement such methodology.

00:16:46.539 --> 00:16:53.380
And lastly, once you are able to successfully deploy such, I think that you could eliminate

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:55.859
bottlenecks within your own systems.

00:16:55.859 --> 00:17:01.219
And for us gathered here today, I think if we free up some time within our own day-to-day

00:17:01.219 --> 00:17:07.180
work functions, we could write more scripts, we could deploy more applications, and I think

00:17:07.180 --> 00:17:09.579
that is a win-win situation for all of us.

00:17:09.579 --> 00:17:13.900
It's an investment that we're making for further down the line.

00:17:14.500 --> 00:17:19.420
Lastly, we would like to thank the following people for their time and assistance for this

00:17:19.420 --> 00:17:20.420
project.

00:17:20.420 --> 00:17:21.420
Thank you.

00:17:21.420 --> 00:17:23.420
And, yeah, thank you.

